## Phase 1 — Scaffold prompt

Paste this as your first message to Gemini CLI.

```
You are helping me set up a personal work assistant built on Gemini CLI. This
is NOT a software project. It is a structured workspace for operational
knowledge work at my bank.

My role: I lead cyber incident response at a large US bank. I work in a
regulated environment where audit trails, decision provenance, and human-in-
the-loop judgment matter more than speed. My communication preference is
plain, direct, unpolished — no pitch language, no marketing tone, no developer
jargon (no "refactor," "CRUD," "slug"). Concrete analogies over abstractions.

My daily work spans five types: full cyber incidents, third-party incidents
(vendor-side), commercial client incidents, other cybersecurity events
(advisories, intel, pre-incident triage), and other corporate tasks
(management asks, audit questions, deliverables, meetings).

This workspace has been cleared by my infosec team and lives in OneDrive,
which syncs across my machines and provides version history.

=== YOUR JOB RIGHT NOW ===

Phase 1: Scaffold the workspace. Create the directory tree, write GEMINI.md,
write README.md, create YAML context stubs with TODO placeholders, create
templates. DO NOT invent content about me. DO NOT solve any real tasks. DO
NOT fill YAML files with example content — I will fill them myself.

=== DIRECTORY STRUCTURE ===

GEMINI.md
README.md

context/
  role.yaml
  organization.yaml
  frameworks.yaml
  playbooks.yaml
  communication-style.yaml

inbox/                             (untriaged drop zone for incoming files)

current/
  cyber-incidents/                 (one subfolder per open incident)
  third-party-incidents/           (one subfolder per open item)
  client-incidents/                (one subfolder per open item)
  cyber-events/                    (one subfolder per open item)
  tasks/                           (one subfolder per non-trivial task)
  audit-queue.md                   (running list of pending audit questions)
  drafts/                          (drafts not yet tied to a specific case)

archive/
  cyber-incidents/
  third-party-incidents/
  client-incidents/
  cyber-events/
  tasks/
  audit/                           (answered audit questions, timestamped)
  summaries/                       (delivered exec summaries, timestamped)

templates/
  incident-record.md               (for cyber-incidents/)
  third-party-record.md            (for third-party-incidents/)
  client-incident-record.md        (for client-incidents/)
  cyber-event-record.md            (for cyber-events/)
  task-record.md                   (for tasks/)
  executive-summary.md
  audit-response.md
  daily-log.md

logs/
  session-log.md                   (append-only record of what you helped with)

=== CASE FOLDER INNER STRUCTURE ===

Every subfolder created under current/cyber-incidents/, third-party-incidents/,
client-incidents/, cyber-events/, and tasks/ MUST follow this inner shape:

  <case-folder>/
    <record>.md        (from the relevant template)
    inputs/            (source materials I drop in, or you extract)
    drafts/            (in-flight outputs for this case)
    outputs/           (delivered outputs, prefixed YYYY-MM-DD of send date)

Document this pattern explicitly in GEMINI.md and include a short note in
README.md explaining it to a human opening the folder.

=== GEMINI.md CONTENTS (critical — write this carefully) ===

Write GEMINI.md as prose, not a bulleted list dump. It should read like a
note from me to a new assistant. Cover these rules:

1. This workspace is operational content, not source code. Do not refactor,
   restructure, or tidy files. Treat them as records to be preserved.

2. The archive/ tree is APPEND-ONLY. Never edit or delete files in archive/.
   When a current/ item is complete, MOVE it to the parallel archive/
   subtree with a YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM- prefix on the folder or file name.

3. Before any substantive task, read the relevant context/*.yaml files. Do
   not guess at my role, authorities, or communication style.

4. At the start of each session, ask (or infer and confirm) whether I'm in
   QUICK mode or SUSTAINED mode:
     - QUICK: one-shot tasks, minimal ceremony, drafts in current/drafts/
     - SUSTAINED: case work (any of the five types), full case folder,
       discipline the timeline, checkpoint as we go

5. WORK TYPE ROUTING. When I describe a new case, help me classify it:
     - cyber-incident: confirmed incident, we're responding
     - third-party-incident: a vendor/partner had an incident, we're
       assessing our exposure
     - client-incident: a commercial client had an incident, we're
       coordinating the bank's response
     - cyber-event: pre-incident or non-incident (advisory, emergency
       directive, intel item, suspicious activity under triage)
     - task: a corporate work item that isn't a security case

   When a cyber-event escalates to an incident, MOVE the folder from
   current/cyber-events/ to current/cyber-incidents/ — do not copy. The
   pre-escalation record is part of the incident record.

6. INPUTS. When I drop a file in inbox/, help me triage it: which case does
   it belong to, or is it a new case? Once identified, move the file to the
   case's inputs/ folder. If the file is .docx, .pdf, or .msg and I ask you
   to work with it, produce a text extraction alongside the original
   (filename.extracted.md) and work from the extraction. The original stays
   as the authoritative source.

7. OUTPUTS. Drafts live in a case's drafts/ folder (or current/drafts/ if
   not tied to a case). When I say a draft is final and I'm sending it:
     a. Copy the final version to the case's outputs/ folder, prefixed
        YYYY-MM-DD-
     b. Also copy exec summaries and audit responses to archive/summaries/
        or archive/audit/ for cross-case rollup
     c. Remove the draft from the drafts/ folder
     d. Log the send in logs/session-log.md
   Never send content directly. I review before anything leaves.

8. Use plain language. Avoid pitch/marketing tone and developer jargon.
   Concrete analogies.

9. CASE LIFECYCLE. Create each case folder as
   YYYY-MM-DD-short-descriptor/. Use the appropriate template from
   templates/ as the record. Append updates to timelines with timestamps;
   do not rewrite history. On close, move the folder to the parallel
   archive/ subtree, prepending the close date to the folder name.

10. SESSION LOG. Every session, append a short entry to logs/session-log.md
    describing what you worked on, what files you touched, and any
    decisions I made.

11. Default to asking one clarifying question when a task is ambiguous. Do
    not invent details to fill gaps.

12. When answering from context/ or archive/, cite the file you pulled from.

13. Yearly rollup: in January, I will ask you to move the prior year's
    archive subfolders into archive/<year>/ subdirectories. Do not do this
    automatically.

14. OneDrive note: if you encounter a file-read or file-write error, it may
    be a sync conflict. Tell me; do not retry silently or create .conflict
    variants.

=== YAML STUB CONTENT ===

Create each context/*.yaml with commented section headers and TODO
placeholders. Do not invent values. Example for role.yaml:

    # role.yaml — fill in before using the assistant for real work
    title: TODO
    organization: TODO
    responsibilities:
      - TODO
    authorities:
      - TODO
    decision_rights:
